english:
  title: 'On the Joy of Riding an Ox: A Discourse on Lee''s Wanderings'
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have long maintained that to truly enjoy the pleasures of mountain and water, one's heart must first be unburdened by worldly attachments and petty concerns. My friend Lee Ju-do, who dwells in Pyeonghai, often rides an ox by moonlight with wine in hand, wandering between peaks and streams. Pyeonghai is renowned for its scenic beauty, and Lee has mastered what ancient wanderers never fully grasped—the subtle mysteries of such journeys.

    When the eye moves swiftly over things, it grasps only their surface; when it lingers, it perceives their essence. The horse runs swift, the ox moves slow. To ride the ox is to choose slowness.

    Imagine the bright moon hanging in heaven, mountains towering, waters stretching wide—above and below merge into one luminous expanse, boundless whether one looks down or up. One regards ten thousand affairs as drifting clouds, sends long whistles into the clear wind, lets the ox wander where it will, and pours wine for oneself as inclination guides. In such a state, the breast becomes serene, and joy naturally arises—something no one bound by attachments could ever achieve.

    Did the ancients know such joy? Perhaps Su Dongpo's wandering at Red Cliff came close. Yet his boat was precarious, lacking the ox's steady security. And when wine ran short and provisions failed, he had to return home to consult his wife—far less convenient than carrying one's own provisions! Those ornate oars of cassia wood and paddle of peony—are they not mere encumbrance? And abandoning the boat to climb afoot—is that not sheer toil?

    Who truly understands the joy of riding an ox? Had such a man once studied at the gate of the sage, I have no doubt that Confucius himself would have sighed in quiet appreciation.
  footnotes:
    - 'Pyeonghai (平海): A scenic region on Korea''s eastern coast, likely in what is now Gangwon Province.'
    - 'Su Dongpo (東坡公): The Song dynasty poet and official Su Shi (1037-1101), famous for his literary and philosophical wanderings. His ''Red Cliff'' remains a celebrated poem about enlightenment through nature.'
    - The final allusion to Confucius suggests that such transcendent joy through nature embodies principles of sage wisdom, elevating Lee's ox-riding beyond mere leisure into a form of spiritual cultivation.
